%S A269156 3,19,60,90
%N A269156 Smallest sum of length of edges and diagonals of an integer polygon with n vertices.
%C A269156 An integer polygon is a convex polygon such that the distance between every pair of vertices is an integer (in some length units).
%H A269156 B. E. Peterson and J. H. Jordan, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/3618764">Integer geometry: some examples and construction</a>, The Mathematical Gazette, Volume 81, Number 490, 1997, pages 18-28.
%e A269156 An equilateral triangle with sides of length 1 has the smallest perimeter. Hence a(3)=3.
%e A269156 The integer quadrilateral with the smallest sum of lengths of edges and diagonals is a trapezium with bases of length 3 and 4, legs of length 2 and diagonals of length 4. Hence a(4)=19.
%Y A269156 Cf. A096872 for minimum diameter.
